{
  "doc_id": "58037",
  "text": "Each video camera is then calibrated both spatially and photometrically, and the video streams synchronized. To do so, we follow the approach described in [CITATION_1] . More specifically, intrinsic parameters are recovered using [CITATION_2] and they are assumed to be constant throughout the recording. Subsequently the pose, i.e., the extrinsic parameters, for each camera at each time instant, are computed with respect to the background geometry by matching the SIFT descriptors [CITATION_3] extracted from the current frame and the SIFT descriptors previously extracted during the SfM procedure. These matches generate correspondences between 2D points in the current frame and 3D points in the background geometry. The pose of that camera at that specific time is recovered by applying the three points algorithm [CITATION_4] . Temporal synchronization of the videos stream is performed using the corresponding audio streams as in [CITATION_5] .",
